Examining Relationships Between Transportation and Health Outcomes Across Public Health Jurisdictions

Author

C. Scott Smith, PhD AICP (Instructor)

Published

February 28, 2024

Introduction

This relatively brief exercise utilizes the suburban Cook County Health Atlas and Chicago Health Atlas indicators to evaluate select public health outcomes relative to transportation access and quality across Cook County. The exercise will make use of indicators derived from local surveys (i.e., Cook County Health Survey and the Healthy Chicago Survey) that are administered annually by the two local health departments. Both surveys are designed to collect neighborhood-level information from residents on such things as health status, risk behaviors, and access to health care to inform and monitor the health status of communities. Download the exercise #4 presentation template to organize data elements and summaries. Submit the completed presentation to the appropriate submission folder on D2L.

Step 1. Create a new R project

This exercise makes use of RStudio, which is available on all DePaul computers. (See download and install instructions below if you are planning to use your own laptop.) In RStudio, create a project within a new directory (e.g., GEO330/exercise_04) of a course folder on your computer. The new directory will serve as your project working directory where you will store files related to exercise #3. Create the following folders within the new exercise-specific directory: (1) âdataâ, (2) âimagesâ, and (3) âscriptsâ.

Install R, RStudio and QGIS

R is a free software environment for statistical computing and graphics. It compiles and runs on a wide variety of UNIX platforms, Windows and MacOS. You can download and install R via the R Archive Network web pages.

RStudio is an integrated development environment (IDE) for R. It has a set of tools built to help R users be more productive with R (and other languages including Python)). It includes a console, syntax-highlighting editor that supports direct code execution. It also features tools for plotting, viewing history, debugging and managing your workspace. You can download RStudio via the Posit website.

Step 2. Create a new R script

In the âFilesâ tab of your RStudio interface (conventionally located on the bottom left screen), navigate to the âscriptsâ folder in your working directory. Create a new R script in the âscriptsâ directory and assign it an intuitive name (e.g., âExercise_04.Râ). You will use this script to manage and execute code all code for this exercise.

Step 4. Review public health indicators on atlases

The suburban Cook County and city of Chicago health atlases are published on similar online platforms. Both atlases provide a wide array of public health indicators on a range of topics. Comprehensive data dictionaries for each of the atlases can be downloaded via the following links (SCC atlas indicator data dictionary; Chicago atlas indicator data dictionary). For this exercise, we will be using indicators derived from each jurisdictionsâ health survey. FigureÂ 1 lists survey indicators for each of the jurisdictions along with their unique identifier keys. Note that the following code was used to create the interactive table. It is for reference only and does not need to be copied into your custom R script.

Code 
# reference API url
topic_list_scc_url <- "https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/api/v1/topics/?format=json&limit=400"

# download data in JSON format
topic_list_scc_json <- fromJSON(topic_list_scc_url)

# convert to dataframe
survey_topic_list_scc <- topic_list_scc_json$results %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  filter(str_detect(name,"CCHS") &
        is_count==FALSE) %>%
  select(name,
         key,
         description) %>% 
  mutate(location = "SCC")

# reference API url
topic_list_chicago_url <- "https://chicagohealthatlas.org/api/v1/topics/?format=json&limit=400"

# download data in JSON format
topic_list_chicago_json <- fromJSON(topic_list_chicago_url)

# convert to dataframe
survey_topic_list_chicago <- topic_list_chicago_json$results %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  filter(str_detect(key,"HCS") &
        is_count==FALSE) %>%
  select(name,
         key,
         description) %>% 
  mutate(location = "Chicago")

# bind SCC and Chicago indicator lists
survey_topic_list <- survey_topic_list_scc %>% 
  bind_rows(survey_topic_list_chicago) %>% 
  relocate(location, .before = name)

Step 5. Create novel county-wide geographic layer for mapping

Use the following code to create a novel geography (N=202) that combines city of Chicago community areas (N=77) and suburban Cook County municipalities (N=125 using 4 square mile threshold area) using GEOJSON data imported from the two health atlases. FigureÂ 2 displays an interactive map of the new geography (i.e., ânovel_geo_cookâ), which includes both suburban Cook County municipalities (dark gray) and community areas (light gray).

# import City of Chicago community areas (N=77) GEOJSON and transform to local projection for spatial analysis (epsg:3435)

community_areas <- st_read("https://metopio.blob.core.windows.net/lalage/atlas/3/shapes/communityareas.topo.json") %>% 
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326) %>% 
  st_transform(3435) %>% 
  rename(geoid = id) %>% 
  mutate(geoid= str_replace(geoid,"1714000-",""),
         location = "Chicago, IL",
         type = "community area")

novel_geo_cook <- places_cook_county %>%

  st_as_sf() %>% 
  st_make_valid()

Step 6. Merge suburban Cook County and city of Chicago health indicators

The next step is to download and merge similar health indicator data from the two atlases for statistical analysis and mapping. Both suburban Cook County and the city of Chicago engage in regular health surveys of their resident populations. Indicators derived from these surveys are shared on the atlas. Many of the indicators on the two atlases are aligned in such a way that allows for comparisons across jurisdictions.

The following code downloads and combines information for a selection of health survey indicators that are comparable across both atlases. Links to jurisdiction-specific thematic maps for the selected indicators are provided below. Using the survey indicators table FigureÂ 1 above, add two additional health indicators to the lists below. That is, add a one-word indicator name to the âa_topic_listâ, and the associated indicator keys to the SCC and Chicago lists in the appropriate format.

  • Adult obesity rate (SCC | Chicago)
  • Neighborhood safety rate (SCC | Chicago)
  • Neighborhood sidewalk quality rate (SCC | Chicago)
  • Neighborhood violence rate (SCC | Chicago)
  • Ease of walking to transit stop rate (SCC | Chicago)
  • Overall health status (SCC | Chicago)
  • Physical inactivity rate (SCC | Chicago)
a_topic_list <- c("obesity","safety", "sidewalk", "violence", "transit", "health", "inactivity") # edit here
a_scc_topic_keys <- c("JG8YZKL","JG8SRFE","JG8IQGF","JG8QFWF","JG8OWII","JG8OLNB","JG8MIQE") # edit here
a_chicago_topic_keys <- c("HCSOBP", "HCSNSP","HCSNSQP","HCSNVP","HCSWTSP","HCSOHSP","HCSPAP") # edit here

# download SCC health survey indicators
for (i in 1:length(a_scc_topic_keys)){

  atopic_key <- a_scc_topic_keys[i]
  atopic_name <- a_topic_list[i]
  
  print(atopic_name)
  
  a_table_name <- paste0("scc_indicator_",atopic_name)

  a_topic_url <- paste0("https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/api/v1/data/?format=json&layer=place&period=2022&population=&topic=",atopic_key)
  
  a_topic_json <- fromJSON(a_topic_url)

  a_topic_df <- a_topic_json$results %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% 
   select(estimate = v,
          se = se,
          geoid = g,
          layer = l) %>%
    mutate(topic = atopic_name)

  assign(a_table_name, a_topic_df)
  
}

# download Chicago health survey indicators
for (i in 1:length(a_chicago_topic_keys)){

  atopic_key <- a_chicago_topic_keys[i]
  atopic_name <- a_topic_list[i]
  
  print(atopic_name)
  
  a_table_name <- paste0("chicago_indicator_",atopic_name)

  a_topic_url <- paste0("https://chicagohealthatlas.org/api/v1/data/?format=json&layer=neighborhood&period=2021-2022&population=&topic=",atopic_key)
  
  a_topic_json <- fromJSON(a_topic_url)

  a_topic_df <- a_topic_json$results %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(estimate = v,
         se = se,
         geoid = g,
         layer = l) %>%
    mutate(topic = atopic_name,
           geoid= str_replace(geoid,"1714000-",""))

  assign(a_table_name, a_topic_df)
  
}

# bind SCC and Chicago indicators together
apattern <- "_indicator_"
alist_indicators <- mget(ls(pattern=apattern))
indicators_all <- rbindlist(alist_indicators)

# remove unneeded tables
rm(list=ls(pattern=apattern))

Step 7. Join indicator attributes with county-wide geographies

Now join indicator attributes to the county-wide geography layer using the code below. This spatially-enabled table will be used in Step 8 to create custom univariate and bivariate maps.

# reformat indicators in wide format
indicators_all_long <- indicators_all %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "topic", values_from = c("estimate","se")) %>% 
  rename_with(~str_remove(., 'estimate_'))

# join indicator data with county-wide "novel" geography layer
indicators_all_long_geo <- novel_geo_cook %>% 
  left_join(indicators_all_long, by="geoid") %>% 
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  drop_na(layer)

Step 8. Examine statistical relationships between selected variables

Use the code below to create a bivariate correlation plot to explore the statistical relationships between the seven downloaded indicator variables.

# subset indicator data for statistical analysis
indicators_all_long_sub <- indicators_all_long_geo %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  select(-starts_with("se"), -c(geoid,name,type, location,layer))
  
# calculate bivariate correlations between all numeric variables
variable_biv_correlations <- cor(indicators_all_long_sub)

# create correlation plot option 1 with correlation values
corrplot_1 <- corrplot(variable_biv_correlations, method="number", col=c("black","white"), order="hclust", bg="lightgrey", tl.col = "grey")

# create correlation plot option 2 with graduated circles
corrplot_2 <- corrplot(variable_biv_correlations, col=c("black","white"), order="hclust", bg="lightgrey", tl.col = "grey")

# display correlation plot option 1
corrplot_1
# display correlation plot option 2
corrplot_2

Step 9. Create custom maps

Use the code below to create two custom single variable (univariate) and bivariate thematic / choropleth maps. Add the maps to slides 2-4 of your presentation and describe the spatial patterns you see.

# Create two custom, single variable (univariate) maps and one bivariate thematic/choropleth map # modify variable(s) to be mapped and legend names/titles for all maps

# map.HEALTH
map.Health <- ggplot() + geom_sf(data=indicators_all_long_geo,
                                  mapping = aes(fill = ntile(health, 5)),
                               size = 0.1) + 
  scale_fill_distiller(name="Health", # edit here
                       palette = "Greys", 
                       breaks = pretty_breaks(),
                       direction = 1) + 
  theme_minimal()

# display map
map.Health

# map.Transit
map.Transit <- ggplot() + geom_sf(data=indicators_all_long_geo,
                   mapping = aes(fill = ntile(transit, 5)), # edit here
                   size = 0.1) + 
  scale_fill_distiller(name="Transit", # edit here
                       palette = "Greys", 
                       breaks = pretty_breaks(n=4),
                       direction = 1) + 
  theme_minimal()

# display map
map.Transit

# create custom bivariate map based on two component variables
# bivariate map data
map.bivariate.data <- bi_class(indicators_all_long_geo, 
                 x = health, # edit here
                 y = transit, # edit here
                 style = "quantile", dim = 3)

# bivariate map 1 plot
# Available palettes: "Bluegill", "BlueGold", "BlueOr", "BlueYl",
# "Brown"/"Brown2", "DkBlue"/"DkBlue2", "DkCyan"/"DkCyan2",
# "DkViolet"/"DkViolet2", "GrPink"/"GrPink2", "PinkGrn", "PurpleGrn", or
# "PurpleOr"

map <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = map.bivariate.data, 
          mapping = aes(fill = bi_class), 
          color = "grey", 
          size = 0.01, 
          show.legend = FALSE) +
  bi_scale_fill(pal = "BlueGold", dim = 3) + 
  bi_theme()

# bivariate map 1 legend
map.legend <- bi_legend(pal = "BlueGold",
                    dim = 3,
                    xlab = "Health", # edit here
                    ylab = "Access", # edit here
                    size = 8,
                    pad_width = 1)

map.bivariate <- ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(map, 0, 0, 1, 1) +
  draw_plot(map.legend, 0.2, 0.45, 0.35, 0.2)

# draw bivariate map
map.bivariate

# Introduction

This relatively brief exercise utilizes the [suburban Cook County Health Atlas](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org) and [Chicago Health Atlas](https://chicagohealthatlas.org) indicators to evaluate select public health outcomes relative to transportation access and quality across Cook County. The exercise will make use of indicators derived from local surveys (i.e., [Cook County Health Survey](https://cookcountypublichealth.org/health-survey/) and the [Healthy Chicago Survey](https://www.chicago.gov/city/en/depts/cdph/supp_info/healthy-communities/healthy-chicago-survey.html)) that are administered annually by the two local health departments. Both surveys are designed to collect neighborhood-level information from residents on such things as health status, risk behaviors, and access to health care to inform and monitor the health status of communities. # Step 6. Merge suburban Cook County and city of Chicago health indicators

The next step is to download and merge similar health indicator data from the two atlases for statistical analysis and mapping. Both suburban Cook County and the city of Chicago engage in regular health surveys of their resident populations. Indicators derived from these surveys are shared on the atlas. Many of the indicators on the two atlases are aligned in such a way that allows for comparisons across jurisdictions.

The following code downloads and combines information for a selection of health survey indicators that are comparable across both atlases. Links to jurisdiction-specific thematic maps for the selected indicators are provided below. *Using the survey indicators table @fig-survey_indicators above, add two additional health indicators to the lists below. That is, add a one-word indicator name to the "a_topic_list", and the associated indicator keys to the SCC and Chicago lists in the appropriate format.*

-   Adult obesity rate ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8YZKL) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSOBP))
-   Neighborhood safety rate ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8SRFE) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSNSP))
-   Neighborhood sidewalk quality rate ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8IQGF) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSNSQP))
-   Neighborhood violence rate ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8QFWF) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSNVP))
-   Ease of walking to transit stop rate ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8OWII) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSWTSP))
-   Overall health status ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8OLNB) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSOHSP))
-   Physical inactivity rate ([SCC](https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/indicators/JG8MIQE) \| [Chicago](https://chicagohealthatlas.org/indicators/HCSPAP))

```{r}
#| eval: true
#| echo: true

a_topic_list <- c("obesity","safety", "sidewalk", "violence", "transit", "health", "inactivity") # edit here
a_scc_topic_keys <- c("JG8YZKL","JG8SRFE","JG8IQGF","JG8QFWF","JG8OWII","JG8OLNB","JG8MIQE") # edit here
a_chicago_topic_keys <- c("HCSOBP", "HCSNSP","HCSNSQP","HCSNVP","HCSWTSP","HCSOHSP","HCSPAP") # edit here

# download SCC health survey indicators
for (i in 1:length(a_scc_topic_keys)){

  atopic_key <- a_scc_topic_keys[i]
  atopic_name <- a_topic_list[i]
  
  print(atopic_name)
  
  a_table_name <- paste0("scc_indicator_",atopic_name)

  a_topic_url <- paste0("https://cookcountyhealthatlas.org/api/v1/data/?format=json&layer=place&period=2022&population=&topic=",atopic_key)
  
  a_topic_json <- fromJSON(a_topic_url)

  a_topic_df <- a_topic_json$results %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% 
   select(estimate = v,
          se = se,
          geoid = g,
          layer = l) %>%
    mutate(topic = atopic_name)

  assign(a_table_name, a_topic_df)
  
}

# download Chicago health survey indicators
for (i in 1:length(a_chicago_topic_keys)){

  atopic_key <- a_chicago_topic_keys[i]
  atopic_name <- a_topic_list[i]
  
  print(atopic_name)
  
  a_table_name <- paste0("chicago_indicator_",atopic_name)

  a_topic_url <- paste0("https://chicagohealthatlas.org/api/v1/data/?format=json&layer=neighborhood&period=2021-2022&population=&topic=",atopic_key)
  
  a_topic_json <- fromJSON(a_topic_url)

  a_topic_df <- a_topic_json$results %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(estimate = v,
         se = se,
         geoid = g,
         layer = l) %>%
    mutate(topic = atopic_name,
           geoid= str_replace(geoid,"1714000-",""))

  assign(a_table_name, a_topic_df)
  
}

# bind SCC and Chicago indicators together
apattern <- "_indicator_"
alist_indicators <- mget(ls(pattern=apattern))
indicators_all <- rbindlist(alist_indicators)

# remove unneeded tables
rm(list=ls(pattern=apattern))

```

# Step 7. Join indicator attributes with county-wide geographies

Now join indicator attributes to the county-wide geography layer using the code below. This spatially-enabled table will be used in Step 8 to create custom univariate and bivariate maps.

```{r}
#| warning: false
#| eval: true
#| output: true

# reformat indicators in wide format
indicators_all_long <- indicators_all %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "topic", values_from = c("estimate","se")) %>% 
  rename_with(~str_remove(., 'estimate_'))

# join indicator data with county-wide "novel" geography layer
indicators_all_long_geo <- novel_geo_cook %>% 
  left_join(indicators_all_long, by="geoid") %>% 
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  drop_na(layer)

```

# Step 8. Examine statistical relationships between selected variables

Use the code below to create a bivariate correlation plot to explore the statistical relationships between the seven downloaded indicator variables.

```{r}
#| warning: false

# subset indicator data for statistical analysis

# calculate bivariate correlations between all numeric variables
```
